(* README *)

1 - Description
    -----------

    T004 is the seeded Rule 30 package. Its final public structure is:

      - Main Constructive Framework
      - Corollary 1
      - Corollary 2
      - Corollary 3

    The Main Constructive Framework consists of the first three phases:

      - Phase 1: the seeded orbit, the No Progenitor Theorem,
        and the compactness-facing replay scaffold for
        `replay_compactness_principle -> forall n, ~ purely_periodic_center_window n`,
      - Phase 2: the constructive cutoff-memory theorem, together with
        the auxiliary compact-trap / hidden-support vocabulary,
      - Phase 3: the mixed-periodicity transport layer and its direct
        semantic impossibility theorem

    The three corollary layers are:

      - Corollary 1: the external classical wrapper under the
        Faithfulness Hypothesis,
      - Corollary 2: the center-real reduction and irrationality layer,
      - Corollary 3: the finite provenance / observation-only layer,
        including the center-strip-free shell question and the
        observation-only tamper-checking impossibility theorem

    This split is deliberate. The constructive core is not asked to prove
    global eventual aperiodicity as a bare classical proposition. It proves
    instead that no closed replay / transport / uniform witness of such a tail
    can survive. Corollary 1 then states the explicit classical soundness
    principle, and Corollary 2 packages the resulting classical conclusion in
    the ordinary language of real arithmetic.

    It separates:

      - observable periodicity of the actual centered window,
      - replay data witnessing that this observable package can be restated
        as a closed periodic object,
      - admissibility data above the seed,
      - and the contradiction obtained once admissibility is present.

    The present Phase 1 compactness corollary is:

      no_pure_periodicity_of_centered_windows :
        replay_compactness_principle ->
        forall n, ~ purely_periodic_center_window n

    The package also exposes the stronger direct semantic endpoint proved
    in the mixed-periodicity layer:

      uniformly_eventually_periodic_from_impossible :
        forall R T P,
          uniformly_eventually_periodic_from R T P ->
          False

    together with the packaged realizability corollary:

      realizable_uniform_periodic_tail_from_impossible :
        forall R, ~ realizable_uniform_periodic_tail_from R

    and the external classical corollary:

      classical_semantics_excludes_eventual_periodic_windows :
        classical_semantic_faithfulness ->
        forall R, ~ eventually_periodic_center_window R

    This is the intended boundary. Phase 3 constructively rules out closed
    uniform witnesses of periodicity; Corollary 1 is the explicit classical
    step that turns that witness-level obstruction into eventual
    non-periodicity of centered windows.

    Corollary 2 then packages the center column as a binary real:

      center_real : R

    It also packages the finite growing-pyramid recipe:

      fueled_center_real : R

    and proves the presentation-independence statement:

      fueled_center_real_eq_center_real :
        fueled_center_real = center_real

    The arithmetic reduction is also separated out explicitly:

      center_real_irrational_if_center_strip_not_eventually_periodic :
        ~ eventually_periodic_bits center_strip ->
        ~ exists q : Q, center_real = Q2R q

    The real reduction now also lands directly in the finite replay
    language:

      center_real_rational_implies_cutoff_replay_package :
        forall q,
          center_real = Q2R q ->
          cutoff_replay_package 0

      fueled_center_real_rational_implies_cutoff_replay_package :
        forall q,
          fueled_center_real = Q2R q ->
          cutoff_replay_package 0

    Here `cutoff_replay_package 0` means a replay package at radius `0`,
    i.e. for the center column.

    The move to `R` does not replace the Rule 30 argument by analysis. It is
    there to package the already fixed center digits as one extensional
    classical object. The philosophical payoff is that the finite
    growing-pyramid recipe and the bi-infinite presentation define the same
    real, and rationality of that real reduces back to a finite replay object
    in the native Rule 30 language.

    It then derives the irrationality consequence:

      center_real_irrational_under_classical_semantics :
        classical_semantic_faithfulness ->
        ~ exists q : Q, center_real = Q2R q

    together with the same conclusion for the finite recipe presentation:

      fueled_center_real_irrational_under_classical_semantics :
        classical_semantic_faithfulness ->
        ~ exists q : Q, fueled_center_real = Q2R q

    The finite interface between Phase 2 and Phase 3 is now also made
    explicit:

      local_target_window_realization_iff_pointwise :
        forall R target u,
          local_target_window_realization R target u <->
          forall x,
            Z.abs x <= Z.of_nat R ->
            step u x = target x

      local_target_window_realization_seed_iff :
        forall R u,
          local_target_window_realization R seed_row u <->
          local_seed_window_realization R u

    Phase 3 also packages any eventual centered tail as a concrete bounded
    cutoff replay object:

      cutoff_replay_package : nat -> Prop

      eventual_periodicity_yields_cutoff_replay_package :
        forall n,
          eventually_periodic_center_window n ->
          cutoff_replay_package n

    So before any later contradiction argument is applied, the eventual-tail
    hypothesis has already been converted into a finite replay package whose
    target row is the canonical cutoff row itself, both in window form and in
    bounded pointwise form.

    The seed-cutoff specialization is also closed:

      local_target_window_realization_of_seed_builds_phase2_memory_certificate :
        forall N u,
          local_target_window_realization (S (S N)) seed_row u ->
          phase2_memory_certificate N u

    and therefore any replay package already sitting at time cutoff `0`
    feeds directly into the Original Sin memory layer.

    The package also exposes the finite shell question:

      manipulation_question_decidable_without_center_strip :
        forall N u,
          { center_strip_free_manipulated N u } +
          { ~ center_strip_free_manipulated N u }

    together with the Phase 2 consequence:

      local_seed_window_realization_forces_center_strip_free_manipulation :
        forall N u,
          local_seed_window_realization (S N) u ->
          center_strip_free_manipulated N u

    and the stronger observation-only impossibility statement:

      no_observation_only_tamper_checker :
        forall R T checker,
          ~ observation_only_tamper_checker R T checker

    This is the recommended semantic reading of the package: no closed
    uniform periodic tail exists for the seeded Rule 30 center, and in
    particular no faithful realizer can package such a tail.

    The compactness route is kept explicit:

      observable periodicity
        + upward admissibility
        -> False

    T004 also proves that the bare finite seed-window matching problem is
    satisfiable at every radius.  So any future compactness obstruction must
    include replay or closure equations, not merely one-step agreement with the
    seed on a bounded interval.

    For that reason the compactness-facing finite object is now:

      finite_replay_problem n horizon

    which keeps the replay equations together with a genuinely bounded
    admissibility witness: the upward step legitimacy is required only on the
    finite radius n + horizon.

    The package also isolates the compactness step explicitly as a premise:

      replay_compactness_principle :
        Prop

    It also proves the bounded periodicity bridge:

      purely_periodic_implies_finite_replay_problem :
        forall n horizon,
          purely_periodic_center_window n ->
          finite_replay_problem n horizon

    Combining that bridge with the Replay Compactness premise and the
    No Progenitor Theorem yields the Phase 1 compactness corollary,
    while the primary semantic interface is the direct Phase 3
    impossibility theorem together with its realizability corollaries
    and the final Faithfulness Hypothesis corollary wrapper.


2 - Public Compilation Surface
    --------------------------

    .
    ├── README
    │
    │      (This file.)
    │
    ├── R01__Phase_One.v
    │
    │      Consolidated Phase 1 theory unit: base dynamics, the seed,
    │      local lemmas, replay/admissibility data, and the
    │      compactness-conditional no-pure-periodicity route.
    │
    ├── R02__Phase_Two.v
    │
    │      Consolidated Phase 2 theory unit: bounded seed-window
    │      realizations, the Original Sin Theorem, and the auxiliary
    │      reverse-side compact-trap / hidden-support vocabulary.
    │
    ├── R03__Phase_Three.v
    │
    │      Consolidated Phase 3 theory unit: mixed-periodicity
    │      impossibility and realizability-facing corollaries.
    │
    ├── R04__1st_Corollary.v
    │
    │      First external corollary layer under the Faithfulness
    │      Hypothesis.
    │
    ├── R05__2nd_Corollary.v
    │
    │      Second corollary layer.  It interprets the center strip as
    │      a binary real, proves that the finite growing-pyramid
    │      recipe yields the same real, isolates irrationality as a
    │      direct consequence of center-strip non-eventual-periodicity,
    │      proves that rational binary reals induce eventually periodic
    │      bit streams, and concludes that the common Rule 30 center
    │      real is irrational under the Faithfulness Hypothesis.
    │
    ├── R06__3rd_Corollary.v
    │
    │      Third corollary layer.  It removes the center strip from
    │      view, asks the residual four-bit syntactic question
    │      "was this manipulated?", proves that question decidable,
    │      classifies the finite reverse-predecessor-carrier ambiguity of the visible
    │      canonical observation, and proves that no checker seeing only
    │      that visible observation can decide canonical versus
    │      tampered hidden predecessor carriers.
    │
    ├── T004__Comprehension.v
    │
    │      Audit-facing index for all three layers, including the strong
    │      semantic endpoint and the external classical corollary.
    │
    ├── T004__Extraction.v
    │
    │      OCaml extraction surface for finite windows, seeded prefixes,
    │      truncations, and assumption reporting.
    │
    └── appendix
           ├── ObservedPeriodRefuter.ml
           │
           │      Extracted OCaml implementation of the finite observational
           │      period refuter for centered canonical windows.
           │
           ├── ObservedPeriodRefuter.mli
           │
           │      Generated OCaml interface for the extracted period-refuter
           │      surface.
           │
           ├── UniformTailWitnessChecker.ml
           │
           │      Extracted OCaml implementation of the bounded uniform-tail
           │      witness checker for candidate periodic tails.
           │
           └── UniformTailWitnessChecker.mli

                  Generated OCaml interface for the extracted witness-checker
                  surface.

    The legacy split route has been consolidated into the eight public
    source files above, and `_CoqProject` now compiles exactly that
    surface.  `T004__Comprehension.v` audits the full public pipeline, with
    `R01__Phase_One.v` through
    `R03__Phase_Three.v` forming the constructive framework and
    `R04__1st_Corollary.v` through `R06__3rd_Corollary.v` forming the
    corollary sequence.


3 - Notes
    -----

    (i)    A progenitor is a finitely supported predecessor.

    (ii)   The No Progenitor Theorem does not say the seed has no
           arbitrary predecessor. It says the seed has no finitely supported
           predecessor.

    (iii)  The audit layer exposes the full public structure explicitly:
           the three constructive phases together with the corollary sequence.

    (iv)   Bare finite seed-window matching is too weak: T004 proves it is
           satisfiable for every radius.

    (v)    The correct finite target for compactness is a bounded replay
           problem, not the bare local predecessor window.

    (vi)   The classical step is explicit: periodicity yields the bounded
           replay problem at every horizon; if every such bounded problem is
           satisfiable, compactness yields admissibility; combined with
           the No Progenitor Theorem this gives a finite replay
           obstruction.

    (vii)  The Phase 2 unit carries both the closed cutoff-memory theorem
           `original_sin_theorem` and the auxiliary compact-trap /
           hidden-support vocabulary used to organize reverse-side descent
           arguments.

    (viii) T004__Comprehension.v is the audit entry point for the package.

    (ix)   The recommended semantic endpoint is not the Phase 1 compactness
           theorem but the direct uniform-tail impossibility theorem in
           Phase 3, together with its realizability corollaries and the
           Faithfulness Hypothesis wrapper in R04__1st_Corollary.

    (x)    The compactness language remains mathematically meaningful as a
           contrapositive packaging of finite replay obstruction; it is not
           the only semantic reading carried by the package.

    (xi)   `R06__3rd_Corollary.v` still does not settle full semantic
           provenance.  It does, however, prove a stronger impossibility:
           once tampering is phrased at the finite predecessor-syntax
           level, no checker that only sees the visible canonical
           observation can decide canonical versus tampered hidden
           predecessor data.
